26:59.566 --> 27:04.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the
"NewsHour": why is a heat
wave baking the Southwest
and grounding flights?;

27:06.533 --> 27:09.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
plus, actor Alan Alda explains
what he has learned on how
to communicate effectively.

27:11.900 --> 27:15.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But first: As we heard, Senate
Republicans are pushing hard
to pass their own bill next

27:16.633 --> 27:18.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
week to replace and overhaul
the Affordable Care Act.

27:18.866 --> 27:23.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
One of the key issues,
major cuts to Medicaid,
the joint federal-state
program that provides

27:23.633 --> 27:27.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
health care to
low-income Americans,
the elderly and disabled.

27:27.400 --> 27:29.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It was expanded under Obamacare.

27:29.600 --> 27:34.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But now 14 million Medicaid
recipients stand to lose that
coverage under a bill passed

27:34.566 --> 27:36.533 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
by the House.

27:36.533 --> 27:40.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Reports out tonight say there
will be even deeper cuts
under the Senate version.

27:40.100 --> 27:44.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Special correspondent Cat Wise
reports from Los Angeles on
how these cuts could directly

27:44.100 --> 27:46.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
affect patients.

27:46.166 --> 27:50.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: A homeless man on
Skid Row hoping to finally
get a roof over his head.

27:52.333 --> 27:56.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A middle-class mom
earning an income to
care of her disabled son.

27:56.033 --> 28:00.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A working-class truck
driver getting care for his
complex medical problems.

28:00.900 --> 28:05.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Three very different lives,
with a common thread now at
risk of being cut: Medicaid.

28:07.900 --> 28:11.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Los Angeles is well known
for its Hollywood stars
with glamorous lifestyles.

28:11.300 --> 28:15.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the city is also home to
many who are less fortunate.

28:15.066 --> 28:18.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The working poor and homeless
here have benefited from
the Affordable Care Act.

28:18.900 --> 28:23.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In fact, about 1.2
million residents gained
health insurance through
the Medicaid expansion.

28:25.033 --> 28:27.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But all that may
be about to change.

28:27.966 --> 28:32.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Republican plan to replace
the Affordable Care Act, passed
by the House of Representatives

28:32.333 --> 28:37.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in May and now being
considered by the Senate,
would fundamentally
alter Medicaid in two

28:37.166 --> 28:39.133 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
key ways.

28:39.133 --> 28:43.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
First, the ACA's Medicaid
expansion -- that offered states
the option of covering most

28:43.400 --> 28:48.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
non-disabled childless adults
with incomes below and just
above the poverty line -- would

28:49.266 --> 28:51.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
end within several years.

28:51.366 --> 28:52.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP, President of the
United States: We're going to
get this passed through the

28:52.600 --> 28:53.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Senate.

28:53.600 --> 28:55.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I feel so confident.

28:55.600 --> 28:58.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: The House bill, which
President Trump cheered in
May, but has since reportedly

28:58.033 --> 29:03.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
called mean, also calls for
converting the entire program
from one with no cap on dollars

29:04.466 --> 29:06.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
spent to one where states
get a fixed amount of money.

29:06.900 --> 29:11.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It would give state
governments more flexibility
about how to spend
Medicaid dollars, but would

29:13.966 --> 29:16.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cut the amount they receive
by more than $800 billion
over a decade, according
to the Congressional

29:17.400 --> 29:18.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Budget Office.

29:18.400 --> 29:20.366 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

29:20.366 --> 29:21.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MITCH MCCONNELL (R-KY), Majority
Leader: I think we will have
ample opportunity to read

29:21.300 --> 29:23.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and amend the bill.

29:23.733 --> 29:26.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAT WISE: A Senate version,
which would eventually
need to be merged with
the House bill before

29:26.533 --> 29:31.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
becoming law, is still being
crafted, but is said to include
many of these same adjustments,

29:33.433 --> 29:36.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
though with a potentially
longer rollback of the
Medicaid expansion.

29:36.666 --> 29:41.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
California stands to lose more
than any other state under
the House version, $6 billion

29:41.600 --> 29:46.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a year starting in 2020, and
more than $24 billion by 2027.

29:48.033 --> 29:49.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Those cuts could have a
big impact on this group.

29:49.900 --> 29:52.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
WOMAN: I think you
have hypertension,
diabetes, neuropathy.

29:52.833 --> 29:57.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: For the last several
years, Los Angeles County
has been deploying teams of

30:00.333 --> 30:03.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nurses, mental health
and substance counselors
and formerly homeless
peer advocates throughout

30:03.933 --> 30:05.933 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Skid Row.

30:05.933 --> 30:09.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their goal is to improve health
outcomes for this medically
complex and costly homeless

30:09.633 --> 30:12.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
population by
giving them a home.

30:12.866 --> 30:17.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This Housing for Health program
uses Medicaid dollars to fund
supportive services, like

30:17.833 --> 30:22.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mental health counseling and
substance abuse treatment in
locations where new housing is

30:22.300 --> 30:24.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
being offered.

30:24.333 --> 30:27.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On the day we tagged along, the
team reconnected with a client
who had been wanting to get

30:27.233 --> 30:28.433 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
off the streets.

30:28.433 --> 30:29.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
WOMAN: Are you familiar
with the (INAUDIBLE)

30:29.233 --> 30:30.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
MAN: No?

30:30.233 --> 30:31.233 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
WOMAN: No?

30:31.233 --> 30:33.266 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
OK.

30:33.266 --> 30:34.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that's like -- that's the
one everyone likes, because
you can get your own room.

30:34.433 --> 30:37.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MAN: That sounds
like my kind of room.

30:37.166 --> 30:38.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: Yes, exactly.

30:38.200 --> 30:39.400 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

30:39.400 --> 30:41.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
WOMAN: It was a blessing
to find him here.

30:41.500 --> 30:46.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We will basically link him to
services and help him get to
the point where he wants to

30:46.666 --> 30:48.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
be.

30:48.800 --> 30:51.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Nearly 3,000 people
have received housing so far,
and the goal is to get 7,000

30:51.833 --> 30:53.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
more off the streets by 2020.

30:53.200 --> 30:55.700 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

30:55.700 --> 30:57.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MITCH KATZ, Director,
Los Angeles County Health
Agency: We have had
dramatic drops in emergency

30:57.633 --> 31:01.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
department visits
and hospitalizations
following housing people.

31:03.800 --> 31:07.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Dr. Mitch Katz is
the director of the Los Angeles
Health Agency, and he has

31:08.066 --> 31:10.100 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
been leading the
county's effort.

31:10.100 --> 31:14.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We met at the Star Apartments,
a 100-unit building in the heart
of Skid Row with a community

31:14.233 --> 31:19.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
garden, various counseling
services and a health
clinic on the main floor.

31:21.200 --> 31:24.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The monthly rent is covered
by county general funds,
donations, and residents.

31:24.333 --> 31:27.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the services provided
are covered by Medicaid.

31:27.966 --> 31:31.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Dr. Katz took me on a tour
of a recently vacated unit.

31:31.633 --> 31:33.666 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

31:33.666 --> 31:37.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MITCH KATZ: You will see that,
although the space is small,
it has everything that you

31:37.233 --> 31:38.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
would need.

31:38.300 --> 31:40.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You have a refrigerator,
stove, sink.

31:40.900 --> 31:44.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's not grand, but it really
changes somebody's life.

31:44.433 --> 31:49.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Over a hundred people
came directly out of the
hospital bed, or directly
from the emergency

31:50.500 --> 31:52.566 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
room, and are now living here.

31:52.566 --> 31:57.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I can take care of them for
way less than it costs to be
in the hospital, and they will

31:59.233 --> 32:01.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
have a much higher-quality life.

32:01.366 --> 32:05.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: The ACA's Medicaid
changes have also been felt
by a much wider swathe of the

32:07.900 --> 32:10.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
population, low-income,
often working adults who
previously had no access
to health insurance.

32:13.366 --> 32:18.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that was the
story for 60-year-old
Jorge Arias, a former
self-employed truck driver.

32:20.366 --> 32:23.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Arias, who has had Medicaid
for the last two years, is a
patient at the Saban Community

32:25.466 --> 32:28.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Clinic, a non-profit federally
qualified health center which
opened its doors to low-income

32:28.866 --> 32:32.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
clients 50 years ago.

32:32.033 --> 32:37.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Last year, Arias had emergency
surgery after a heart specialist
determined he had three

32:37.766 --> 32:38.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
blocked arteries.

32:38.700 --> 32:40.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Without insurance, he says:

32:40.766 --> 32:44.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JORGE ARIAS, Medicaid Recipient:
I would not even be alive, you
know, because, no medications,

32:44.333 --> 32:46.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
no doctors.

32:46.300 --> 32:49.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JULIE HUDMAN, CEO, Saban
Community Clinic: Well, we see
about 18,000 to 20,000 patients

32:49.166 --> 32:54.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a year; 10,000 of them have
Medicaid, and over 8,000 of
them got it with the expansion

32:55.766 --> 32:57.266 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
under the ACA.

32:57.266 --> 32:59.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CAT WISE: Julie Hudman
is the CEO of the clinic.

32:59.966 --> 33:04.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JULIE HUDMAN: Before we had
the ACA, someone would come in
and, depending on their income,

33:04.233 --> 33:08.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
we'd take a co-pay,
and it typically was
around $18 per person.

33:08.133 --> 33:13.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, when a patient comes
in with Medicaid, we receive
about $200 for the visit.

33:15.133 --> 33:18.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The difference between the
$18 and the $200, $225 is, you
know, a huge source of revenue

33:21.000 --> 33:24.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for us, and allows us
to stabilize, to keep
our doors open, and then
actually expand services.

33:26.133 --> 33:30.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MAN: So, how have
you been this week?

33:30.333 --> 33:31.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
WOMAN: Fine.

33:31.333 --> 33:33.433 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Yes, I'm good.

33:33.433 --> 33:35.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Some of those new
services include mental health
counseling, which could be cut

33:35.533 --> 33:39.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
back if the clinic
loses funding.

33:39.466 --> 33:43.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Traditional Medicaid programs,
like those for the disabled
and long-term care for the

33:43.033 --> 33:46.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
elderly, could also be impacted.

33:46.300 --> 33:51.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Victoria and Steve Rosen
are the proud, adopted
parents of 16-year-old
Max, who has a number

33:53.300 --> 33:56.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of health problems due
to prenatal exposure
to drugs and alcohol.

33:56.833 --> 33:58.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
VICTORIA ROSEN,
California: So this is Max.

33:58.900 --> 34:03.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
When we first met him
in the NICU, he had a
very rough beginning.

34:03.200 --> 34:08.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CAT WISE: Max is the
recipient of a Medicaid-funded
program called In-Home
Supportive Services.

34:10.866 --> 34:15.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Victoria earns about
$3,500 a month through
the program to help Max
with things like personal

34:15.733 --> 34:17.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
care and feeding.

34:17.666 --> 34:21.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That financial support has
been key for the family because
helping Max is a full-time

34:21.933 --> 34:25.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
job, and Victoria hasn't been
able to work outside the home.

34:25.066 --> 34:27.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
VICTORIA ROSEN: It helps
us survive, basically.

34:27.033 --> 34:30.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I mean, before this, we
were, you know, in debt.

34:30.800 --> 34:33.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We don't spend a
lot of extra money.

34:33.600 --> 34:35.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And all the money
we spend is on Max.

34:35.666 --> 34:40.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: But many supportive
Medicaid service programs like
this one are considered optional

34:42.533 --> 34:46.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
under traditional Medicaid,
and if states have to take on
more financial responsibility

34:49.066 --> 34:53.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for Medicaid with the new
Republican plan, health analysts
and program leaders say the

34:53.900 --> 34:57.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
optional services
are likely to be cut.

34:57.500 --> 35:00.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
To the Rosens, that doesn't
make a lot of sense.

35:00.200 --> 35:02.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
STEVE ROSEN, California:
IHSS saves money.

35:02.833 --> 35:07.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It would be more expensive to
take care of someone like Max
in an institutional setting

35:09.333 --> 35:11.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
than it is to have
him in his own house.

35:11.566 --> 35:16.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Many Republicans say
these programs may be important,
but Medicaid is simply out

35:17.166 --> 35:19.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of control.

35:19.166 --> 35:21.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL CANNON, Cato Institute:
Medicaid has grown into this
incredibly wasteful program,

35:21.233 --> 35:26.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rife with fraud, siphoning lots
of money away from the people
the program should be helping.

35:28.066 --> 35:31.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Michael Cannon is
the director of health policy
studies at the Cato Institute,

35:31.266 --> 35:33.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a libertarian think tank.

35:33.266 --> 35:37.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Cannon is concerned the current
legislation being considered
by Congress wouldn't go far

35:37.600 --> 35:42.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
enough in axing federal
Medicaid regulations and turning
over control to the states.

35:42.600 --> 35:45.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL CANNON: So, what
Congress should be doing here
is saying to the states, look,

35:45.933 --> 35:48.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we don't know how to run these
programs better than you.

35:48.400 --> 35:52.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We will continue our
contribution to your
Medicaid programs, but
we're going to give

35:52.433 --> 35:54.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you a fixed amount of money.

35:54.433 --> 35:57.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not going to grow from
one year to the next, but we're
also going to give you full

35:57.900 --> 36:02.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
flexibility to run your
programs the way you think
is best for your state.

36:04.766 --> 36:06.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
States will have a much greater
incentives then to eliminate
fraud, to make sure that

36:06.766 --> 36:11.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
those Medicaid dollars are
being spent on the people the
program was meant to help,

36:11.300 --> 36:13.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and not on the people the
program wasn't meant to help.

36:13.533 --> 36:17.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: Back in Los Angeles,
the health department's Dr.
Katz says he has no problem

36:17.800 --> 36:20.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
working within a budget as
long as it is a fair one.

36:20.533 --> 36:22.166 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

36:22.166 --> 36:24.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MITCH KATZ: If you
give me flexibility,
I can do a better job.

36:24.500 --> 36:26.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And I could do a better
job for less money.

36:26.933 --> 36:29.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But I can't do 70
cents on the dollar.

36:29.866 --> 36:32.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Then, I'm actually going
to have to cut services.

36:32.100 --> 36:37.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CAT WISE: While the health care
debates continue in Washington,
the teams on Skid Row are still

36:39.066 --> 36:42.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
hitting the streets looking
for people to help, and hoping
they can do so for a very

36:42.200 --> 36:43.733 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
long time.

36:43.733 --> 36:48.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Cat
Wise in Los Angeles, California.

36:52.700 --> 36:57.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now let's turn
to the extreme heat wave baking
the West and Southwest parts

37:03.333 --> 37:04.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the country.

37:04.800 --> 37:07.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Temperatures are well
above the 100-degree mark.

37:07.000 --> 37:12.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In California, it was 127
degrees yesterday in Death
Valley, 122 in Palm Springs.

37:13.866 --> 37:16.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Phoenix, the temperature
is expected to top out
at 118 degrees today.

37:16.600 --> 37:21.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In fact, it's been so hot
there, more than 40 flights
were canceled or delayed because

37:22.933 --> 37:26.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
some planes can't safely
lift off in that heat.

37:26.533 --> 37:31.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A new analysis published in the
journal "Nature Climate Change"
this week also said climate

37:32.933 --> 37:35.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
change is leading to more
heat waves in general.

37:35.000 --> 37:39.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It found that 30 percent of the
world's population is exposed
to potentially deadly heat for

37:40.833 --> 37:43.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
20 days per year or more.

37:43.100 --> 37:47.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's the subject of our weekly
segment on the Leading Edge
of science with Miles O'Brien.

37:47.400 --> 37:49.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Let's start with what's
happening in Phoenix.

37:49.533 --> 37:51.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Miles, you have flown
for a long time.

37:51.666 --> 37:54.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We have always heard of
flights being delayed
because it's too cold.

37:54.800 --> 37:56.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How can a flight not take
off because it's so hot?

37:56.933 --> 38:00.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Yes, Hari, if
it weren't for the snow and
ice, the winter would be the

38:00.200 --> 38:05.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
perfect time to fly, because
a wing achieves flight, it
derives lift based on the number

38:06.900 --> 38:09.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of air molecules
that surround it.

38:09.133 --> 38:13.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, as the temperature heat
up, those molecules command.

38:13.433 --> 38:16.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We know that, when you
warm things up, things
expand generally.

38:16.333 --> 38:21.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So there are fewer
air molecules, so it
takes greater amount of
speed for that aircraft

38:21.133 --> 38:23.133 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to fly.

38:23.133 --> 38:26.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if the runway isn't long
enough to support that -- in
other words, if the temperature

38:26.100 --> 38:30.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is so high that there are so
few molecules there to lift
the wing that you don't have

38:30.333 --> 38:33.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
enough runway to get going
fast enough, you're grounded.

38:33.166 --> 38:37.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
so this is still smaller
planes that were affected.

38:37.033 --> 38:39.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What's the difference
with the bigger planes?

38:39.033 --> 38:43.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, the larger
planes, the Boeing 737s, the
big airliners, are designed

38:43.233 --> 38:46.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to operate in a wider range of
circumstances, for one thing.

38:46.266 --> 38:51.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are kind of a global
product that has to operate in
all kinds of intense conditions.

38:51.000 --> 38:55.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, frankly, it just
costs more to certify
them to these parameters.

38:55.833 --> 39:00.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In addition, a 737, for example,
has a lot more potential
payload, so you can take off

39:02.000 --> 39:04.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
some cargo and still
fly the mission.

39:04.233 --> 39:09.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
These smaller planes
are not designed with
as much versatility, and
because they're smaller,

39:09.000 --> 39:13.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they have less capability
to reduce the payload
and thus take off.

39:13.266 --> 39:17.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And really, ultimately, they
have charts in there that a
pilot has to look at, and there

39:17.400 --> 39:21.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will be a maximum temperature,
given the altitude of
the field, et cetera.

39:21.866 --> 39:24.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And if you exceed that, you
legally cannot take off.

39:24.900 --> 39:29.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: There are
lots of runways that are too
short to deal with this kind

39:29.366 --> 39:31.333 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of heat.

39:31.333 --> 39:33.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we talked about in Phoenix,
but, say, a place like La
Guardia is just as confined

39:33.833 --> 39:37.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
or San Francisco is
just constrained by a
certain amount of space.

39:37.266 --> 39:38.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Yes, so
researchers looked at this.

39:38.733 --> 39:42.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The La Guardia runway is about
7,000 feet, runways there.

39:42.233 --> 39:47.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And while that's about 20 feet
above sea level, and thus the
air is denser there, by virtue

39:49.166 --> 39:53.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of where it is and it doesn't
get quite as hot, nevertheless,
at that length, you still

39:55.633 --> 39:57.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
- - there are still some
parameters and constraints
that we have to be
watching as the climate

39:57.966 --> 40:00.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
gets warmer.

40:00.100 --> 40:03.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This goes into the larger
subject, Hari, of how our
civilization is designed.

40:03.100 --> 40:07.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When you're thinking about a
beach house on a barrier island
or a runway at La Guardia

40:07.600 --> 40:12.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or at Phoenix Sky Harbor,
we have a finely-tuned
civilization, and as
the temperature goes

40:14.566 --> 40:17.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up, even though it has only
gone up a degree Celsius over
a hundred years, it does create

40:18.833 --> 40:21.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
pockets of these heat waves.

40:21.466 --> 40:24.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're not exactly sure
why, probably because the
jet stream is weakening
and causing high-pressure

40:24.866 --> 40:26.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
systems to park in these places.

40:26.766 --> 40:30.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I spoke with a climate
scientist who has looked
into this extensively.

40:30.766 --> 40:35.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's at Columbia University --
Radley Horton is his name --
as part of a series I did for

40:35.666 --> 40:37.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the weather app MyRadar.

40:37.733 --> 40:40.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RADLEY HORTON, Columbia
University: If we look
at the last decade
or two, we are seeing

40:40.366 --> 40:45.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
twice as many record-breaking
extreme heat events, cities
that are breaking their daily

40:47.366 --> 40:50.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
record highs for a given day,
compared to the ratio compared
to the number of cities

40:52.000 --> 40:54.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
having record-breaking
cold temperatures.

40:54.166 --> 40:58.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you make temperatures just
a couple degrees warmer on the
hottest days, that means much

40:58.366 --> 41:02.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more demand for air
conditioning, for
example, which means much
greater risk of the power

41:02.766 --> 41:07.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going out, precisely at those
temperatures, those times when
people are so sensitive to

41:09.166 --> 41:11.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
just a little more warming from
a public health perspective.

41:11.833 --> 41:14.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: That goes a
bit to that Goldilocks effect
you are talking about, because

41:14.933 --> 41:19.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
even our infrastructure and
our systems are built for us
to be within a certain range.

41:19.100 --> 41:21.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Exactly.

41:21.166 --> 41:24.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's why we need
to be really watching the
effects of climate change.

41:24.866 --> 41:29.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's easy to dismiss
a one-degree Celsius
increase and say, well,
that's not a big deal,

41:29.833 --> 41:34.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but, in isolated locations, in
specific locations, whether it's
Phoenix or whether it's Miami

41:36.766 --> 41:40.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Beach or whether it's another
city that has a sea level
problem that it is dealing with,

41:42.600 --> 41:45.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or whether it's California
dealing with wildfires,
those particular pockets,
those problems are

41:45.733 --> 41:50.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
exacerbated by that
overall increase in the
temperature of the climate,
the overall temperature

41:52.233 --> 41:54.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the planet.

41:54.333 --> 41:58.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it causes changes to our
weather systems which we're
just beginning to understand.

42:00.133 --> 42:02.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Researchers are just
getting a handle on it.

42:02.133 --> 42:05.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So in the
case of this news about Phoenix
and the air -- do airlines,

42:05.333 --> 42:09.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who think about buying planes
years and years out -- these are
hundreds of millions of dollars'

42:09.433 --> 42:13.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
worth of purchases -- do they
think differently about what
kind of jets to buy or where to

42:13.266 --> 42:15.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
park all those jets, in a
place with a long runway?

42:15.766 --> 42:20.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Hari, I
think this is something
the aviation industry
has not gotten out ahead

42:21.233 --> 42:23.300 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of.

42:23.300 --> 42:25.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I suspect there are a lot of
conversations going right now
as we have seen this record

42:25.566 --> 42:27.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
heat wave.

42:27.600 --> 42:31.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There was a similar record
heat wave last year as well
which caused similar problems.

42:31.066 --> 42:36.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So the airlines are going to
have to contend with this, the
airliner makers, and airports

42:36.833 --> 42:38.700 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
as well.

42:38.700 --> 42:41.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The longest runway at Phoenix
Sky Harbor is a little
more than 11,000 feet.

42:41.500 --> 42:43.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They might have to think
about extending that runway.

42:43.533 --> 42:44.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What about La Guardia, though?

42:44.533 --> 42:45.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is that even possible?

42:45.766 --> 42:48.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Is it possible to
even consider that?

42:48.100 --> 42:52.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All these things get factored
into the consequences
of climate change and
how we as civilization

42:53.166 --> 42:55.266 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
can adapt to it.

42:55.266 --> 42:59.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
science correspondent Miles
O'Brien, thanks so much.

43:00.133 --> 43:04.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: You're welcome.

43:06.333 --> 43:10.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now a
lesson in communication
from an unlikely, but
very familiar source.

43:13.400 --> 43:16.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's the latest addition to
the "NewsHour" Bookshelf.

43:16.033 --> 43:18.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Brown has that.

43:18.133 --> 43:22.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: One enormous
turn in the life of Alan Alda,
his 11- year run in the 1970s

43:24.766 --> 43:29.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and '80s as the star of
"MASH," one of the most beloved
programs in television history.

43:31.500 --> 43:32.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ALAN ALDA, Author, "If
I Understood You, Would
I Have This Look on
My Face?": Hello, and

43:32.733 --> 43:34.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
welcome to "Scientific
American Frontiers."

43:34.800 --> 43:38.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Another, by
his own account, came in 1993,
when he began to host the PBS

43:39.833 --> 43:42.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
series "Scientific
American Frontiers."

43:42.333 --> 43:47.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was a non-scientist learning
on the go, using his trademark
humor and wit to get the

43:48.800 --> 43:51.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
experts to explain complicated
ideas in accessible language.

43:51.966 --> 43:54.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALAN ALDA: What keeps the
water from going in here?

43:54.100 --> 43:55.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I mean, it's...

43:55.333 --> 43:56.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MAN: Well, it's
actually tapered.

43:56.833 --> 43:57.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If you look at the hatch,
it's like a porthole.

43:57.666 --> 43:58.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ALAN ALDA: Oh, I see.

43:58.966 --> 44:01.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MAN: And pressure
pushes them down.

44:01.133 --> 44:03.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN ALDA: What I brought
to it was curiosity and
a huge fund of ignorance.

44:03.766 --> 44:05.833 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

44:05.833 --> 44:08.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN ALDA: And I just was
after them until it could fill
up the ignorance a little bit

44:08.566 --> 44:10.566 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with real stuff.

44:10.566 --> 44:15.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But that process of connecting
with them, getting them to
be who they were, because

44:17.600 --> 44:22.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they were worried about
getting me to understand it,
so it was much more personal.

44:24.000 --> 44:26.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's when I realized
that you could build on that.

44:26.733 --> 44:28.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You can help people
do that all the time.

44:28.933 --> 44:31.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
OK, now he's leaving.

44:31.533 --> 44:35.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: First, he
worked to help scientists
and science writers do
it all the time, helping

44:35.133 --> 44:40.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to found the Center for
Communicating Science at Stony
Brook University in New York.

44:42.166 --> 44:45.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now comes a book for the rest
of us, with the colorful title
"If I Understood You, Would

44:46.200 --> 44:48.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I Have This Look on My Face?"

44:48.266 --> 44:53.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Alan Alda and I met recently at
Lisner Auditorium in Washington
before he gave a talk about

44:54.166 --> 44:56.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the problem and promise
of communicating.

44:56.166 --> 45:00.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN ALDA: What I think I found
is, that it's all based on a
personal connection, that if

45:02.466 --> 45:05.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I can sort of understand in some
way, make some approximation
of what you are thinking

45:07.900 --> 45:11.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and feeling, it's easier
for me to get inside your
head with my message.

45:13.433 --> 45:17.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If I don't know how you're
receiving it, if I can't see
how it's landing on you, then

45:17.933 --> 45:20.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm just spraying it at you.

45:20.033 --> 45:22.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm just trying to pour it
over your head, but I'm not
really connecting with you.

45:22.733 --> 45:27.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, that connection -- this
is what I don't understand --
that connection with another

45:27.066 --> 45:28.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
person feels so good.

45:28.933 --> 45:30.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Why do we retreat from it?

45:30.533 --> 45:32.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I don't understand that.

45:32.666 --> 45:36.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: We're living in
a time where there's not only
skepticism, but even outright

45:36.433 --> 45:40.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
hostility from a lot of
people towards science.

45:40.266 --> 45:42.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Is that just a
communication problem?

45:42.300 --> 45:47.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN ALDA: I think it's largely
a communication problem, because
there has to be trust, and

45:49.166 --> 45:53.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you get trust through --
one way you get trust is
through good communication.

45:54.166 --> 45:55.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There are lives at stake.

45:55.233 --> 45:56.266 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Take doctors.

45:56.266 --> 45:58.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

45:58.233 --> 46:02.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN ALDA: When patients
regard their doctors as being
empathic, at least one study has

46:04.833 --> 46:09.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
shown that the patients are
19 percent more likely to
follow the doctor's advice.

46:10.566 --> 46:13.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now, in that 19 percent, I
imagine some lives are at stake.

46:13.100 --> 46:15.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes,
so some of this is
life-and-death communication.

46:15.300 --> 46:16.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ALAN ALDA: Yes.

46:16.300 --> 46:17.300 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

46:17.300 --> 46:19.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

46:19.433 --> 46:22.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN ALDA: Science needs to
be understood by the public,
so they can support science.

46:22.000 --> 46:27.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't tell the people I
care about the most the most
important thing I can tell them,

46:28.033 --> 46:30.066 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that I do care.

46:30.066 --> 46:33.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For Alda, better
communicating starts with better
person-to-person relating,

46:33.966 --> 46:36.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a concept he had to
learn as a young actor.

46:36.566 --> 46:38.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ALAN ALDA: I knew you
were supposed to relate
in the beginning.

46:38.866 --> 46:40.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

46:40.366 --> 46:42.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALAN ALDA: And I would do
the best I could to relate.

46:42.433 --> 46:45.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I thought it meant leaning
into the other person's face,
so I was sort of stooped over

46:45.766 --> 46:47.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
most of the time.

46:47.333 --> 46:49.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:49.800 --> 46:52.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALAN ALDA: But, little
by little, I realized you
can relate to somebody
on the stage even

46:52.000 --> 46:53.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
if their back is turned to you.

46:53.533 --> 46:55.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You pick up whatever
clues you can.

46:55.633 --> 46:59.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And when you don't have clues
to pick up, you can estimate
what they're probably thinking

46:59.366 --> 47:04.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by virtue of what's just been
said, or what you have said,
or what you have just written

47:04.133 --> 47:06.133 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
them.

47:06.133 --> 47:10.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can picture what the
reader is thinking with
each sentence you put down.

47:10.033 --> 47:12.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It really affects all
forms of communication.

47:12.766 --> 47:16.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In several
chapters of the book, you
describe these training sessions

47:16.533 --> 47:18.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that you had with
scientists and many others.

47:18.800 --> 47:21.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But then you talk about
improv classes, right?

47:21.966 --> 47:23.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Improv, we think of as comedy.

47:23.733 --> 47:25.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ALAN ALDA: I know.

47:25.400 --> 47:29.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Most improvisation that
people are aware of is
comedy improvisation.

47:29.066 --> 47:30.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But that's not what we teach.

47:30.733 --> 47:35.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We teach a much purer
form of improvisation in
the form of exercises.

47:37.100 --> 47:41.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they're all designed one
on top of the other, starting
with a very basic kind of

47:43.200 --> 47:47.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
exercise that enables you to
do the next one, and then that
enables you to do the next one,

47:47.700 --> 47:51.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and they all put you in
touch with the other person.

47:51.166 --> 47:55.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You have to observe the
other person, and really
carefully to improvise.

47:55.300 --> 48:00.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have to know -- I have to
know, from your body language
and your face, what you're doing

48:01.200 --> 48:02.133 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and what you're thinking.

48:02.133 --> 48:03.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm reading your face right now.

48:03.100 --> 48:04.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's really fun.

48:04.100 --> 48:05.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Let's make it...

48:05.100 --> 48:06.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

48:06.100 --> 48:07.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What's going on?

48:07.100 --> 48:08.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

48:08.100 --> 48:10.133 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ALAN ALDA: Yes.

48:10.133 --> 48:12.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, I hear you following me,
and then I hear you thinking,
I wonder what I will ask

48:12.000 --> 48:13.000 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
next?

48:13.000 --> 48:14.000 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

48:14.000 --> 48:15.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Really?

48:15.000 --> 48:16.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You could see that?

48:16.000 --> 48:17.666 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

48:17.666 --> 48:18.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ALAN ALDA: Yes, from
-- yes, mostly when you
look down at the paper.

48:18.333 --> 48:19.266 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

48:19.266 --> 48:20.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes, right.

48:20.066 --> 48:21.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's a dead giveaway.

48:21.000 --> 48:22.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Hmm.

48:22.233 --> 48:23.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ALAN ALDA: Yes, but
I'm picking it up.

48:23.000 --> 48:24.000 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
You know.

48:24.000 --> 48:26.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's so funny.

48:26.033 --> 48:28.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Once in a while I will be
talking to somebody and I will
think I'm connected to them.

48:28.766 --> 48:30.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I will say, wait a second.

48:30.366 --> 48:32.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
In my head, I will say this.

48:32.166 --> 48:33.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What color is his eyes?

48:33.500 --> 48:36.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What color are his eyes?

48:36.233 --> 48:37.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What's the shape of his nose?

48:37.233 --> 48:38.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

48:38.833 --> 48:40.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And then you realize,
what, you're not really
paying attention.

48:40.900 --> 48:43.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAN ALDA: I got -- I realize,
when I think back, there's
been sort of a blob where your

48:43.100 --> 48:44.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
face would -- should be.

48:44.766 --> 48:46.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

48:46.200 --> 48:48.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I hope I
haven't dissolved to blobness.

48:48.100 --> 48:50.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ALAN ALDA: No, you're
not blobby at all, no.

48:50.066 --> 48:51.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: OK.

48:51.066 --> 48:53.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you.

48:53.100 --> 48:55.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's good to know, and also
good to see in his work with
scientists and writers an

48:55.466 --> 48:59.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
attempt to bridge the worlds
of science and the arts.

48:59.433 --> 49:04.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALAN ALDA: They didn't used
to be kept apart so much.

49:06.433 --> 49:09.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Science and art, or the arts
and humanities often were --
in Greek times and later, were

49:11.866 --> 49:16.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
considered to be different
aspects of the same inquiry,
the same exploration of being

49:17.566 --> 49:19.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
alive in the universe.

49:19.766 --> 49:24.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think they're long-lost
lovers, yearning to be reunited.

49:25.900 --> 49:28.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
There's nothing -- they
should be reunited.

49:28.333 --> 49:33.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're reuniting them with
this work on communication,
because it's both an
art and a science to

49:34.500 --> 49:38.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
figure out what's the best way
to learn to communicate better.

49:38.766 --> 49:43.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: All
right, Alan Alda's book
