50:16.033 --> 50:19.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"NewsHour" recently got a
behind-the-scenes look at the
one-of-a-kind instrument from

50:19.533 --> 50:21.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
those who know it best.

50:21.133 --> 50:25.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Cavern historian John
Shaffer starts us off.

50:25.133 --> 50:30.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN SHAFFER, Luray
Caverns Corporation: Luray
caverns is home to the
largest musical instrument

50:33.800 --> 50:37.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in the world, the
Great Stalacpipe Organ.

50:37.733 --> 50:42.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it plays the stalactites.

50:42.533 --> 50:46.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The organ was created
by Leland W. Sprinkle.

50:46.133 --> 50:51.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mr. Sprinkle toured the caverns
in 1954 with his young son,
and, at that time, the guides

50:53.066 --> 50:57.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
would tap stalactites to
show that the different sizes
give off different tones.

50:57.633 --> 51:02.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LARRY MOYER, Operations Manager:
What he did was take rubber
mallets and a concept of an

51:03.966 --> 51:05.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
organ and put it all
together Into an instrument.

51:05.900 --> 51:07.433 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm Larry Moyer.

51:07.433 --> 51:12.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I am operations manager for
the Great Stalacpipe Organ.

51:14.300 --> 51:18.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're actually standing
inside the organ as it plays,
because the stalactites cover

51:18.566 --> 51:21.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
over three-and-a-half
acres around us.

51:21.433 --> 51:25.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Basically, we call it
like a player-type piano.

51:25.733 --> 51:30.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the sheet of plastic is
your song, and as the drum
rotates, the metal brushes fall

51:30.300 --> 51:35.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
into contact through
holes in the plastic
and sends the notes out.

51:36.766 --> 51:38.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, on occasion, we will
have an organist present.

51:38.766 --> 51:42.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
OTTO PEBWORTH, Organist: A pipe
organ produces its sounds by
forcing air through columns.

51:44.966 --> 51:49.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What we are doing here is,
we are actually playing a
37-note percussion instrument.

51:51.133 --> 51:53.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
My name is Otto Pebworth.

51:53.166 --> 51:57.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I play the organ here at Luray
Caverns, and I have been playing
pipe organs now for close

51:59.300 --> 52:03.266 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to 30 years.

52:03.266 --> 52:07.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's very settling,
very soothing.

52:07.166 --> 52:12.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I just have a chance just
to stop and let everything
go quiet and make music.

52:13.466 --> 52:17.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And that's what makes
it the nicest thing.

52:17.566 --> 52:22.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A room like this lends itself
more towards the more peaceful
things like "Moonlight Sonata"

52:24.733 --> 52:28.966 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
or some of the Bach preludes.

52:28.966 --> 52:33.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Stalacpipe Organ is a
totally unique instrument
unto itself, and,
because of that, you can

52:40.433 --> 52:45.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
just hear something that
is just totally natural
and totally special.

52:46.200 --> 52:51.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Can't be duplicated.

